==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Careen
<hw>Ca*reen"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p.
p.</pos> <conjf>Careened</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Careening</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OF.
<ets>cariner</ets>, F. <ets>car⟦eacute⟧ner</ets>, fr. OF.
<ets>car⟦egrave⟧ne</ets>, the bottom of a ship, keel, fr. L.
<ets>carina</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Naut.)</fld> <def>To cause (a vessel) to
lean over so that she floats on one side, leaving the other side out of
water and accessible for repairs below the water line; to case to be off
the keel.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Careen</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Careen
<hw>Ca*reen"</hw> <pr>(<?/)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To incline to
one side, or lie over, as a ship when sailing on a wind; to be off the
keel.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Careenage</ent>⟦br⟧
